====================================================================
üìå SQL STRING FUNCTIONS & DATABASE COMMANDS (NOTES + EXAMPLES)
====================================================================

These commands & functions are used to:
‚úî Explore databases  
‚úî Manipulate text data  
‚úî Format output  
‚úî Perform pattern-based operations  

====================================================================
# 1Ô∏è‚É£ DATABASE EXPLORATION COMMANDS
# ---------------------------------------------------------------

SHOW DATABASES;
‚Üí Displays all available databases in MySQL server.

USE world;
‚Üí Selects the "world" database for execution.

SHOW TABLES;
‚Üí Displays all tables inside the selected database.

====================================================================
# 2Ô∏è‚É£ UPPER() & LOWER()
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
Used to convert text into uppercase or lowercase.

SELECT name, UPPER(name), LOWER(name)  
FROM country;

USE:
‚úî Data formatting  
‚úî Case-insensitive comparisons  

====================================================================
# 3Ô∏è‚É£ CONCAT() FUNCTION
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
Used to join multiple values into a single string.

SELECT name, code, continent,  
CONCAT(continent,'-',code,'regex')  
FROM country;

USE:
‚úî Merge columns  
‚úî Create formatted output  

====================================================================
# 4Ô∏è‚É£ CONCAT_WS() (With Separator)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
WS ‚Üí With Separator

SELECT name, continent,  
CONCAT_WS('-', continent, code, 'regex')  
FROM country;

ADVANTAGE:
‚úî Cleaner syntax  
‚úî Automatically handles NULL values  

====================================================================
# 5Ô∏è‚É£ SUBSTR() / SUBSTRING()
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
Extracts part of a string.

SYNTAX:
SUBSTR(column, start, length)

Examples:

-- Start from first character
SELECT name, SUBSTR(name, 1)  
FROM country;

-- Extract last 5 characters
SELECT name, SUBSTR(name, -5)  
FROM country;

====================================================================
# 6Ô∏è‚É£ SUBSTR() WITH CONDITIONS
# ---------------------------------------------------------------

-- Matching first character of name & continent
SELECT name, continent,  
SUBSTR(name,1,1), SUBSTR(continent,1,1)  
FROM country  
WHERE SUBSTR(name,1,1) = SUBSTR(continent,1,1);

-- Match first 3 characters
SELECT name, continent, SUBSTR(name,1,3)  
FROM country  
WHERE SUBSTR(name,1,3) = 'Alg';

====================================================================
# 7Ô∏è‚É£ LIKE OPERATOR (Pattern Matching)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------

SELECT name, continent  
FROM country  
WHERE name LIKE 'Alg%';

% ‚Üí matches zero or more characters

====================================================================
# 8Ô∏è‚É£ INSTR() FUNCTION
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
Used to find position of a character inside a string.

SELECT name, INSTR(name,'e')  
FROM country;

Returns:
‚úî Position of character  
‚úî 0 if character not found  

====================================================================
# 9Ô∏è‚É£ LENGTH() vs CHAR_LENGTH()
# ---------------------------------------------------------------

SELECT LENGTH('yash');
‚Üí Returns bytes used to store string.

SELECT CHAR_LENGTH('yash');
‚Üí Returns total number of characters.

USE:
‚úî CHAR_LENGTH() for text length  
‚úî LENGTH() for storage size  

====================================================================
# üîü TRIM(), LTRIM(), RTRIM()
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
Used to remove extra characters/spaces.

SELECT CHAR_LENGTH('   gaurav   ');

SELECT TRIM('gauravnnnnn');

-- Remove specific character from both sides
SELECT TRIM(BOTH 'n' FROM 'gauravnnnnn');

SELECT name, TRIM(BOTH 'a' FROM name)  
FROM country;

====================================================================
# 1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ LPAD() & RPAD()
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
Used to pad string from left or right.

SELECT name, population,  
LPAD(population, 9, '0')  
FROM country;

USE:
‚úî Formatting numeric values  
‚úî Display consistency  

====================================================================
SUMMARY
====================================================================

‚úî SHOW DATABASES / USE / SHOW TABLES ‚Üí DB navigation  
‚úî UPPER(), LOWER() ‚Üí text case handling  
‚úî CONCAT(), CONCAT_WS() ‚Üí join strings  
‚úî SUBSTR() ‚Üí extract text  
‚úî LIKE ‚Üí pattern matching  
‚úî INSTR() ‚Üí find character position  
‚úî LENGTH() ‚Üí bytes  
‚úî CHAR_LENGTH() ‚Üí characters  
‚úî TRIM() ‚Üí remove unwanted characters  
‚úî LPAD(), RPAD() ‚Üí formatting output  

END OF NOTES.
====================================================================
